\subsection{Different EVs isolation methods}
In literature different ways to isolate EVs are reported. Three methods are:
\begin{itemize}
\item Nickel-base isolation (NBI): exploits the charge of the EVs (negative) using beads;
\item Size exclusion chromatography (SEC): filter based on the size of the molecule;
\item Ultracentrifugation (UCFG): heaviest molecules (pallet) is discarded and only the surnatant (EV) is retained.
\end{itemize}

Usually all three methods are used. This because no method is perfect, as the EVs in our blood are heterogeneous and each method isolates different subpopulations. This is particular important in liquid biopsies: if the EVs only came from of type of cells, the choice of the method does not change the result that much. Hence multiple analysis methods are required to avoid batch effects.

\subsection{Challenges}
\begin{itemize}
\item Evidence of high variability of EVs populations in terms of EVs isolation method
\item No standard de facto for the analysis of the EVs transcriptome;
\item Dealing with plasma samples, multiple populations of EVs are present, some of which are relevant to cancer, while other are not;
\item The RNA signal deriving from multiple populations is difficult to interpret
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Approaching deconvolution}
Deconvolution is the process through which, from mixed signal after EVs isolation and RNA sequencing, we can differentiate and characterize the different population of vesicles and molecules.\\
